Description: Cranial elements of juvenile Aotus nancymaae (Aotus107)

Parts.PartDescription: The ethmoid contributes to the cranial base and facial skeleton
The frontal forms bilaterally and contributes to the cranial base and vault of the skull
The maxilloturbinals form bilaterally as part of the nasal capsule
The maxillae form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The nasals form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The palatines form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The parietals form bilaterally as part of the cranial vault
The temporals form bilaterally and contribute to the cranial base and vault of the skull
The zygomatics form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The mandible forms bilaterally and comprises the lower jaw of the skull
The occipital contributes to the cranial base and vault of the skull
The maxilloturbinals form bilaterally as part of the nasal capsule
The maxillae form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The nasals form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The palatines form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The parietals form bilaterally as part of the cranial vault
The temporals form bilaterally and contribute to the cranial base and vault of the skull
The zygomatics form bilaterally as part of the facial skeleton
The sphenoid is a midline structure at the center of the skull and contributes to the cranial base, cranial vault, and even the facial skeleton
The vomer is a midline structure that contributes to the nasal septum
